courses.learning_outcomes:
It is expected that by the end of this course students will be able to:

 identify common features of academic texts;
 identify an appropriate topic and conduct research for an academic essay;
 select and organise relevant information into a structured, coherent text;
 avoid acts of academic dishonesty by documenting, quoting, paraphrasing, summarising and synthesising sources appropriately;
 formulate an academic argument with logical reasoning and supporting evidence;
 critically evaluate claims and corresponding evidence;
 adopt a process writing approach;
 deliver presentations purposefully, effectively and confidently; and
 review and reflect on their own language learning.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. understand and identify common features of academic writing and speaking;
2. identify common academic text structures and apply this knowledge to enhance comprehension and analytical skills;
3. conduct topic, purpose and audience analyses when writing academic texts;
4. conduct research to read widely and critically, and evaluate digital source materials to assess their credibility;
5. paraphrase, summarize, synthesize, and quote reading material appropriately and purposefully, using APA style;
6. organize ideas into a cohesive and coherent text, employing logical reasoning and analysis to strengthen the connections between ideas;
7. engage in peer review to evaluate others work;
8. deliver oral presentations and engage effectively and confidently with questions (as both presenter and audience member) and with the audience; anddeliver oral presentations effectively and confidently to small groups (or online if circumstances dictate); and
9. utilize online language resources to facilitate self-directed language learning.

Primary Learning Outcomes:

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. express ideas orally using clear and comprehensible language;
2. identify and interpret a text's main message and attitude;
3. understand, evaluate and respond critically to information in persuasive texts;
4. identify common features of academic texts;
5. understand and implement a process-based approach to writing tasks;
6. write a coherent expository text showing a degree of grammatical accuracy, lexical range, and syntactic variety and complexity; and
7. avoid plagiarism by using appropriate writing strategies.

Secondary Learning Outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. reflect on their own language learning
2. utilize independent learning strategies

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. Identify premises (including unstated assumptions) and conclusions of inductive arguments;
2. Represent the flow of an argument through standardization and diagramming;
3. Analyse the use of persuasive techniques in English language spoken, written and multimedia texts;
4. Evaluate the acceptability, relevance and strengths of arguments; and
5. Apply effective source-use skills.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. Understand the purpose, function, structure and language of reflective writing and informational writing;
2. Produce the above-mentioned text types;
3. Understand content-related and subject-specific language and vocabulary; and

4. Use them appropriately both within and outside of performing arts.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. Analyze a literary text using different critical theories;
2. Compose an original, logical and well-reasoned academic paper in the form of a literary analysis essay;
3. Deliver an analytical presentation/discussion based on their literary analysis essay; and
4. Undertake in-depth analysis and evaluation/critique of their own written work and the work of their classmates.

Upon completion of this course, you will be able to:

1) demonstrate confidence in impromptu speaking;
2) write a professional email using the appropriate tone, style, vocabulary and content;
3) create a presentation outline; and
4) present ideas convincingly to a professional audience in a group oral presentation.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Employ common persuasion techniques, language, and rhetorical structures to formulate and present spoken and written arguments during discussion, presentation and essay writing;
2. Understand and practice discussion skills and language in an academic setting;
3. Summarize, paraphrase and synthesize reading material from original sources to support a thesis;
4. Demonstrate the correct use of vocabulary, sentence structure, grammar, and APA format in writing a formal essay;
5. Deliver a well-organized persuasive academic presentation to classmates and teachers to share meaningful research findings; and
6. Field a question-and-answer session following a presentation.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. write a research proposal;
2. conduct literature search and write literature reviews;
3. apply lab report writing skills;
4. write abstracts for research study; and

5. give an academic presentation.

