courses.learning_outcomes:
In general, through the course students will learn to:

1. understand the structure and style of academic texts;
2. demonstrate academic writing skills focusing on specific academic genres; and
3. give well-researched persuasive presentations effectively using appropriate organizational patterns.

More specifically, by the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:

a) read an academic research article and identify key components including the research question, hypotheses, methodology, findings and conclusion;
b) summarize an academic research paper both verbally and in writing;
c) respond critically to a research paper by spelling out clear criteria of evaluation and support review content with evidence and examples;
d) recognize and demonstrate language features in the academic register;
e) research for quality input and organize such input to form a logical, coherent persuasive presentation using apt organizational patterns;
f) demonstrate verbal and non-verbal delivery skills when giving presentations; and
g) support presentations with data and visuals in a skillful manner.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. understand the structure and style of architectural documents;
2. demonstrate architectural literacy with a focus on specific genres;
3. communicate ideas that are well-structured and convincing in writing; and
4. express views clearly in impromptu speeches.

