courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. apply principles of good writing to plan and revise professional documents;
2. write project proposals and project reports effectively using the conventions of standard written English;
3. give a short oral presentation on a project proposal;
4. express ideas with a range of formal vocabulary and grammatical structures; and

5. utilize online resources for independent English learning.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

- understand the academic writing conventions in their discipline;
- identify the components of a research paper;
- synthesize sources and write an analytical literature review;
- describe and discuss findings effectively; and

- write a concise and coherent research proposal.

By the end of this course students will be able to:

1. Analyze the basic structure of an essay and use that analysis to structure their own writing;
2. Compose original, logical and well-reasoned essays by demonstrating their awareness of the issues involved, by distinguishing between opinion and fact, by recognizing opposing points of view and underlying assumptions, by using supporting evidence and by choosing and applying a variety of writing strategies;
3. Undertake in-depth analysis and evaluation/criticism of their own written work and the work of other students in the class;
4. Deliver an analytical discussion of an academic essay; and
5. Demonstrate university-level competence in grammar and syntax.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. Improve their critical reading skills through a survey of numerous food-related texts;
2. Write reflective texts and comprehensive summaries;
3. Expand their English language proficiency through the use of everyday media technologies;
4. Collaborate with peers to create and produce their own video programme;
5. Conduct audience and purpose analyses for summaries and video presentations;
6. Enhance their English-speaking skills through discussion of food-related topics;
7. Continue to develop their research skills; and
8. Engage in self-directed learning.

