2) understand the importance of rhetoric in speeches;
3) apply Ciceros five rhetorical stages: invention, disposition, style, memory and delivery; and

4) write and deliver formal and informal speeches effectively.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

1. demonstrate a critical understanding of what meaningful intercultural communication entails;
2. demonstrate the ability to recognize and appreciate cultural and linguistic diversity;
3. make reasoned verbal and non-verbal choices in intercultural encounters;
4. produce coherent, insightful accounts of their intercultural experience in English; and
5. reflect on and assess their L2/ cultural self-awareness and intercultural communication skills, and set realistic goals for further enhancement of their English language proficiency, intercultural competence, and global-mindedness.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

